\begin_layout Title
Using Markov processes to model textual sentiment in FARC-Colombia peace
 negotiations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Leslie Huang
\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
New York University Department of Politics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
This M.A.
 paper is submitted in partial requirement of the PhD in politics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
Adviser: Arthur Spirling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Peace negotiations can stretch on for years and are often marred by continued
 fighting, obfuscated by public bluffing, and complicated by internal factionali
zation.
 How can we assess whether progress is being made, measure actors' willingness
 to negotiate, or measure the impact of violent attacks on the peace process?
 This paper uses sentiment analysis as a new method that offers quantitative
 answers to these questions.
 With a new dataset of texts from the ongoing (2012-present) peace talks
 between the Colombian government and the Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias
 de Colombia (FARC), I use measures of textual sentiment to predict each
 actor's willingness to negotiate over time.
 I also model the responsiveness of sentiment to sentiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How do we measure 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how things are going
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in peace negotiations? Analysis of the progress of peace processes, such
 as in the Middle East, has tended to be case-specific or game theoretical.
 Often these accounts are complicated by an inability to discern whether
 actors are sincere and by the disconnect between unitary negotiants (government
, rebel) and the cacophony of factions that each contains.
 To date, some research has offered theories explaining the variable effect
 of violent attacks on derailing peace talks, and theories for the relationship
 between government concessions and the level of terrorist activity.
 Other research has examined the texts of peace agreements to better understand
 the relationship between peace survival and specific agreement provisions.
 However, there is no research that analyzes texts issued during ongoing
 peace negotiations, nor has sentiment analysis previously been used to
 study peace negotiations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper makes several original contributions.
 First, I collected a new dataset of texts from the Colombian government
 and FARC, in addition to jointly released statements, all of which were
 issued during an ongoing conflict and negotiation process (2012-2016).
 Second, I bring in several new methods from psychology and natural language
 processing for measuring that ineffable quantity, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how things are going.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 I use text analysis techniques to model each actor's willingness to negotiate
 as a function of their textual sentiment.
 I also use sentiment analysis to model how one actor's sentiment responds
 to another actor's sentiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are obvious difficulties in quantifying the status of negotiations;
 however, understanding these processes has valuable real-world implications.
 Better measurement of the effects of attacks on often-fragile negotiations,
 for example, could indicate strategies that facilitate agreement and cut
 short a violent conflict.
 Understanding how sentiment responds to sentiment may yield insights about
 signalling and bluffing not only in peace negotiations but also in the
 exchanges between countries that avoid or lead down the path to war.
\end_layout

