\begin_layout Subparagraph*
The Colombian conflict.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FARC (Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia) was founded in 1964 the aftermath
 of the ten-year period of civil war known as La Violencia.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The group's official name is Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia--Ejérci
to del Pueblo (People's Army), or FARC-EP.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Originally a Marxist insurgency seeking to overthrow the government, FARC's
 supporters were mainly communists and rural peasants.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CFR"

\end_inset

 The group's tactics included murder, kidnappings for ransom, disappearances
 of civilians and security personnel, and extortion; less widely known abroad
 is their use of landmines, which have resulted in thousands killed or maimed,
 and their kidnapping and forced conscription of child soldiers.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Ejército de Liberación Nacional (ELN; National Liberation Army), a smaller
 and also Marxist group, has also contributed to violence and instability
 during the same period and has also engaged in murder, kidnappings, violence,
 extortion.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CFR"

\end_inset

 ELN began pursuing cooperation with FARC and peace talks with the government
 as FARC's peace process came underway over the last several years.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 FARC's current circumstances stem from a major shift in the 1980s and 1990s,
 when the group began to tax cocaine producers but soon became involved
 in cocaine production itself, sparking the formation of right-wing paramilitary
 groups such as the Autodefensas Unidas de Colombia (AUC; United Self-Defense
 Forces of Colombia) that battled FARC about, inter alia, control over drug
 trafficking.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wilson_center"

\end_inset

 Notorious until recently as the longest-running guerrilla insurgency in
 the Western Hemisphere, the violence has claimed the lives of more than
 200,000 civilians and displacing millions,
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bbc_ceasefire"

\end_inset

 and FARC, the paramilitary groups, and the government have all been accused
 of human rights abuses.
 (The AUC was also labelled a terrorist organization and was involved in
 drug trafficking as well prior to being disbanded in the mid-2000s.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "colombiareports_auc"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the tenure of president (now senator) Álvaro Uribe from 2002-2010,
 the government cracked down on Marxist groups and drug traffickers, significant
ly reducing the strength of FARC and other armed groups.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CFR"

\end_inset

 FARC's willingness to negotiate is generally attributed in part to this
 crackdown.
 Peace talks, brokered by Cuba and Norway, commenced in the fall of 2012
 in Havana and have been championed by president Juan Manuel Santos.
 The talks were limited to an agenda of six topics: agrarian reform/land
 development; political participation; ending of the conflict (i.e.
 ceasefire, post-conflict justice, disarmament, and reintegration); illegal
 drugs; victims; and implementation.
 Despite negotiating preliminary agreements for the topics on the agenda,
 which will be included in the final peace deal, Santos's approval ratings
 have plummeted over the years, as has public optimism about the talks.
 An agreement faces not just the skepticism of the public but also vociferous
 opposition of right-wing politicians such as Uribe, as well as some members
 of the military, that initially disapproved of negotiating with FARC and
 oppose agreement provisions that, in their view, would give the former
 rebels political representation and amnesty instead of prosecution for
