\begin_layout Section
Theory and hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why does it matter how talks are going? It is not a stretch to suggest that
 impressions or assessments of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how the talks are going
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 affect the views of the public, nor it is an exaggeration to claim that
 decisions made by negotiants during talks may be colored by answers to
 or beliefs about questions such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how serious is the other party about peace?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how hard are they pushing for their demands?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 This paper offers new methods of measurement that get past the vagueness
 or relativism in the way these questions are stated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The answer to the first question, whether the other party is serious about
 negotiations, is significant for two reasons.
 To use FARC-Colombia as our example: The government wants to know, given
 the political cost of continuing to negotiate, whether an avowedly Marxist-Leni
nist group will actually follow through on a peace deal that almost certainly
 would not include the implementation of a Marxist economic-political system.
 Second, regardless of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

truth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 about FARC's seriousness or how hard they are bargaining behind closed
 doors, popular impressions (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

FARC is stalling for time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the government isn't driving a hard enough bargain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) will affect the government's bargaining behavior and demands in public
 and in private, its level of military operations, and certainly its rhetoric,
 as the government has to answer to its political opponents and, eventually,
 in the next cycle of elections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, peace talks are often characterized by mistrust and an inability
 to know whether the other party's statements are sincere.
 For instance, Santos's government long refused to stop military operations
 against FARC, and FARC frequently used its unilateral ceasefires to call
 for a bilateral ceasefire.
 The government's decision has been seen as a safeguard thwarting a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

long con
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 being played by FARC--that is to say, continued military operations would
 prevent FARC from using the negotiations as a cover to buy time to increase
 their military strength.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "battaglino_lodola"

\end_inset

 A variety of concerns likely contributed to the government's suspicions:
 first, the criticism of politicians such as Uribe; second, continuing FARC
 attacks; and third, the fact that negotiations may very well fall apart
 without producing an agreement for various reasons.
 Although this paper focuses only on the negotiation process leading up
 to a peace agreement, mistrust can extend to the implementation of a deal
 (e.g.
 FARC would be wary of disarming or giving up secret information such as
 its members' locations if it thought the government would renege).
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
E.g.
 changes in relative military strength may cause either side to change its
 mind about deciding the outcome of the conflict at the negotiating table
 rather than on the battlefield.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph*
Peace negotiations literature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the above discussion suggests, current assessments of an actor's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

seriousness about peace
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 factor in the level and nature of ongoing violence.
 However, to date the analysis of peace negotiations has not utilized sentiment
 analysis.
 Instead, perhaps because 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

actions speak louder than words,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the focus of much of the empirical research in this field is on violence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance, Kydd and Walter offer a game theoretical explanation for why
 extremist violence during peace negotiations can sometimes derail talks
 by revealing information about the rebel group's capacity or willingness
 to control extremist factions.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kydd_walter"

\end_inset

 A driving force underlying this research is the inability for one negotiant
 to discern whether the other is sincere, bluffing (potentially intererested
 in an agreement but overstating their demands to get a better deal), or
 uninterested in peace and stalling (to allow military forces to regroup),
 based on their words alone.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cf.
 a rationalist explanation for war based on on the incentives of both parties
 to misrepresent their resolve to go to war and their military power.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fearon"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other research on negotiations and violence, Bueno de Mesquita theorizes
 that violence increases after government concessions because more extreme
 members are left in control of their organization after moderate members
 accept the concessions.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "demesquita_conciliation"

\end_inset

 The peace process with FARC, with more than fifty regional fronts but a
 unified central command that has remained in control throughout the peace
 talks and is unquestioned in speaking for its fighters, does not exemplify
 a (perhaps unintentional) divide-and-conquer strategy of the kind discussed
 by Bueno de Mesquita.
 Nevertheless, this area of research underscores the fact that we are interested
 in understanding not just the effect of violence on peace talks, but also
 how events at the negotiating table affect the level of violence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As this discussion demonstrates, measuring actors' willingness to negotiate
 during a peace process can inform our understanding of violence during
 peace talks as well as our understanding of the dynamics of how agreements
 are or are not reached.
 This paper introduces a new tool for measuring actors' willingness to negotiate
 based on sentiment analysis of their actual words, and a new method for
 using sentiment to model the responsiveness of actors to each other's words.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I present a regime-switching Markov model that estimates an actor's willingness
 to negotiate using measures of negative and positive emotion.
 To validate the results from this model, I predict there is a positive
 relationship between a predicted state of high willingness to negotiate
 and the sentiment and incidence of joint statements.
 When FARC and/or the government are predicted to be in a conciliatory rather
 than a hardline state, joint statements are more likely to occur and their
 sentiment is likely to be more positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I also test the relationship between extremism and increased use of third-person
 plural pronouns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second part of the paper, I model the responsiveness of sentiment
 to sentiment using another Markov process.
 I hypothesize that actors are more likely to respond with the same level
 of sentiment.
 In other words, if FARC issues a statement with high (positive) sentiment,
 the following government statement is more likely to respond with high
 rather than low (negative) sentiment, and vice versa.
\end_layout

