\begin_layout Subsection
Sentiment measures.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper uses the Spanish version of the Linguistic Inquiry and Word Count
 (LIWC), which was first developed in English by Pennebaker.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pennebaker_liwc01,pennebaker_liwc07"

\end_inset

 The LIWC methodology reflects Pennebaker et al.'s approach to text analysis,
 which centers around 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

examin[ing] people's social and psychological states by analyzing their
 use of function and emotion words.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pennebaker_chung"

\end_inset

 the former being words such articles or pronouns that are relatively devoid
 of content.
 Consequently, the LIWC measures are very simple: words belonging to specific
 categories--parts of speech (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

articles,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pronouns
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) that are the aforementioned function words, or types of emotion (within
 the categories of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

positive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

negative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, there are subcategories such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimism
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

anxiety or fear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)--are counted, and their share of the total words in the document is calculated
 as a percentage.
 The Spanish LIWC was translated and augmented (e.g.
 additional Spanish synonyms for words translated from the English) by Ramírez-E
sparza, Pennebaker, García, and Suriá Martínez.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ramirez_esparza_liwc"

\end_inset

 LIWC has been used to analyze texts written by individuals from terrorist
 organizations (and translated into English), e.g.
 transcripts of statements by Osama bin Laden and Ayman al-Zawahiri.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pennebaker_chung"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I use the following categories of sentiment: positive emotion, negative
 emotion, and third-person plural pronouns, which have been found to be
 used at higher rates by extremist groups.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pennebaker_chung"

\end_inset

 The LIWC measures are admittedly crude word counts; the categories of words
 are not tailored for political science purposes or for the conflict of
 interest; and the dictionaries are intended for the analysis of personality
 traits of individual authors, not organizations.
 Nevertheless, the LIWC sentiment measures can reveal insights into the
 nature of the documents under analysis.
 Other measurement methods, such as Principal Component Analysis (PCA),
 proved to be unsuitable, probably owing to the high variance in the word
 counts of documents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modelling hidden states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first estimation task is to use the shares of positive and negative
 sentiment in texts to model a Markov regime-switching model in which the
 latent regimes are discrete states that represent the government or FARC's
 willingness to negotiate.
 This model focuses on one actor at a time; in the second part of this paper,
 we will look at how sentiment responds to sentiment subsequently.
 In other words, we are interested in the random variable that represents
 FARC's (or the government's) willingness to negotiate--i.e.
 whether FARC is in a hardline or conciliatory state--which is directly
 unobservable, and is therefore hidden.
 However, we can observe a stream of FARC documents whose sentiment emanates
 from the latent state that FARC is in at the time.
 (For the purposes of simplifying this discussion, I assume a state space
 with two possible, discrete states, but the model can be generalized to
 any number of states.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This hidden Markov model (HMM) is a special case of a Markov process.
 The sequence of hidden states is a Markov chain: the probabilities of being
 in a hardline or conciliatory state, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{C}$
\end_inset

, respectively, exhibit the Markov property, namely that the probability
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{H}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{C}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 depends only on the realization of the state 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{H}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{C}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the realization of state at 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 captures all information about what occurred prior to 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

.
 I assume that the process is stationary, i.e.
 the probability of moving from state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to state 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 does not depend on how long the process has been in state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At each time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 the process is at a state that is hidden or unobservable; however, from
 each state we can observe its emissions, or symbols, 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{t}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The probability of an observed emission 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 depends only on the state 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jurafsky"

\end_inset

 The probability of a stream of observations 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{1},...O_{T}$
\end_inset

 is computed using the forward-backward algorithm, a procedure that optimizes
 the process of summing over all of the hidden state sequences that could
 have generated that the stream of observations.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rabiner1989tutorial"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, the observed sequence of emissions is a stream of loessed
 sentiment measures, for example percent negative emotion words in FARC
 statements (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.01,0.12,0.04,0.01)$
\end_inset

).
 We are interested in the corresponding sequence of hidden states which
 generated the sequence of emissions: for example 
\begin_inset Formula $(S_{H},S_{H},S_{C},S_{H}).$
\end_inset

 We are also interested in the transition probabilities, the probability
 of moving from 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}=S_{i}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t+1}=S_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 These probabilities are represented in transition matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 below:
\end_layout

