 approach and optimize the number of states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Optimizing the number of states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ideal number of states can be identified by the Bayesian information
 criterion (BIC) and the Akaike information criterion (AIC) values.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In other applications of hidden Markov models, the number of states is not
 optimized because it and the labels attached to the states tend to determined
 by substantive criteria: e.g.
 in medical examples, values for various indicators of health that fall
 within certain ranges correspond to pre-set states, and in economic examples,
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bull
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 markets are modelled with two states that clearly correspond with economic
 indicators.
 This paper uses a more agnostic approach.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To keep interpretation across the FARC and government models comparable,
 I specify the same number of latent states.
 The substantive interpretation of the model accommodates small numbers
 of latent states: for instance, two latent states would correspond to a
 dichotomy between 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hardline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conciliatory,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 while three latent states might represent low, moderate, and high levels
 of willingness to negotiate, representing hardline, moderate and conciliatory
 regimes, respectively.
 However, as the number of states increases, the substantive interpretation
 of transition probabilities across these states becomes more challenging.
 Moreover, a higher number of states means that fitting the model becomes
 difficult because transitions between any two given states may be rare
 or not happen at all.
 I weigh these considerations against the models' log-likelihood, BIC, and
 AIC values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Labelling the states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because HMM estimation does not attach substantive labels to the states,
 such labelling must be done post-estimation.
 I explore two possible methods.
 First, I use the distributions of the negative and positive sentiment measures
 to rank the unlabelled states in order of the relative willingness to negotiate.
 For example, the state with the highest mean positive emotion and lowest
 mean negative emotion should correspond to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness to negotiate state (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conciliatory
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), while the state with the lowest mean positive emotion and the highest
 mean negative emotion should be the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness to negotiate state (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hardline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 I also use a multi-choice decision matrix to optimize the ranking of states
 based on the average sentiment measured in each unlabelled state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modelling sentiment response.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second part of this paper uses a simple Markov process to model the
 response of sentiment to sentiment.
 The irregularity of the data does present some challenges, as there are
 stretches in the time-ordered sequence of FARC and government texts where
 little alternation occurs.
 (For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $F,F,F,G,G,G,G,F$
\end_inset

.) This is partly owing to the fact that the dataset includes roughly twice
 as many statements from the government as from FARC and that both actors
 sometimes release multiple statements on the same day.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I assume that the sequence of time-ordered statements during a time interval
 represents a single Markov process, like a back-and-forth debate in which
 each text responds to the document that immediately preceded it.
 This means that a FARC document could respond to a previous FARC document,
 or a government document could respond to a government document.
 Repetitive issuances, e.g.
 a series of low-sentiment documents, might reveal a strategy where actors
 make public denunciations, perhaps to get better terms at the negotiating
 table.
 Our main interest, however, is whether an actor's response mirrors the
 other actor's sentiment: for instance, if, following a FARC statement with
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sentiment, it is more likely that the following government statement is
 also 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sentiment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To categorize overall sentiment of these texts as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 I created a new measure defined by LIWC-based research showing that in
 normal usage, positive emotion words occur twice as frequently as negative
 emotion words.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pennebaker_chung"

\end_inset

 I constructed an indicator for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

