\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper is a first attempt at applying text and sentiment analysis methods
 from psychology to the study of conflict negotiation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further research could build on this paper's findings in a number of ways.
 First of all, the dataset can be updated to include statements leading
 up to the August 2016 peace agreement announcement (and up to the future
 referendum on the agreement).
 Additional analysis could look at the relationship between the sentiment
 of texts from the peace process and the final document itself.
 Given that provisions of a peace agreement can predict whether peace will
 survive, much could be learned from the study of the process that produces
 such agreements.
 A comparative study would lend further credence to sentiment analysis as
 a measurement tool for the progress of peace talks; such data, however,
 is not always available from both sides of a conflict, nor are dictionaries
 such as LIWC available in all languages.
 Although using a general dictionary means that these results are more extendabl
e than they might have been with a dictionary specific to a particular conflict
 (e.g.
 one that includes terms specific to a war or its belligerents), developing
 a dictionary with political science-specific terms would be advantageous
 for more refined analysis that goes beyond simply negative or positive
 sentiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, there are a number of methodological advances that further research
 might undertake.
 Labelling the latent states estimated by a hidden Markov model is essentially
 a classification problem that could be resolved using machine learning
 techniques.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the relationship between sentiment and the level of violence is
 of obvious importance.
 With disaggregated data on the types of violence (e.g.
 bombings, kidnappings, murders, etc.), further research may be able to unearth
 the relationships between specific kinds of attacks and sentiment, and
 reveal insights about peace process spoilers.
\end_layout

